  <h2>What Cabernet Sauvignon Tastes Like</h2>

  <p>Cabernet Sauvignon usually leads with cassis, blackberry, cedar, and graphite. In cooler climates it can show herbs or green pepper. What matters most is the structure: Cabernet feels firmer, more tannic, and more built for protein than Merlot.</p>

  <p>That is why Cabernet dominates steakhouse wine lists. It handles salt, char, and fat well. Young bottles can feel hard if they are opened too early, but when the wine is good, that backbone is the point rather than a flaw.</p>

  <h2>What Merlot Tastes Like</h2>

  <p>Merlot is usually softer, rounder, and more immediately generous. Expect plum, red cherry, cocoa, and herbs instead of Cabernet's darker cassis-and-cedar frame. The tannins are lower, so the wine feels easier earlier.</p>

  <p>That does not make Merlot simple. It just makes it more forgiving. Great Merlot can still be deep, serious, and age-worthy, but it gets there with texture and fruit rather than grip and tension.</p>

  <h2>When To Choose Each</h2>

  <p><strong>Choose Cabernet Sauvignon</strong> when the meal centers on steak, lamb, burgers, or aged cheese. It is also the better pick when you want to cellar bottles or prefer more structure than softness.</p>

  <p><strong>Choose Merlot</strong> when the meal is lighter, the crowd is mixed, or you want a red that is easier to enjoy right now. It is usually the safer answer for roast chicken, pork, mushroom dishes, and casual dinners.</p>

  <p>If you are unsure, ask yourself one question: do you want grip or glide? Cabernet gives grip. Merlot gives glide.</p>

