      <p class="text-gray-700 text-sm">A richer, more serious Merlot with enough density to convert Cabernet drinkers who think Merlot must always be soft or forgettable. It keeps the smoother texture but adds the depth that stronger red-wine buyers usually want.</p>
      <p class="text-xs text-wine-600 mt-2"><strong>Variety:</strong> Merlot</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <h2>Buying By Situation</h2>

  <p><strong>For steak night:</strong> buy Cabernet first. The tannin and darker fruit are built for beef, char, and salt.</p>

  <p><strong>For roast chicken, pork, or mushroom dishes:</strong> Merlot is often the better answer because it stays softer and does not dominate the plate.</p>

  <p><strong>For gifting:</strong> Cabernet usually has the easier prestige sell because buyers recognize the name faster. Merlot becomes the smarter gift only when you know the recipient prefers smoother reds.</p>

  <p><strong>For value shopping:</strong> Merlot often wins in the middle tiers. Cabernet carries more reputation tax, especially from famous regions.</p>

  <p><strong>For building a cellar:</strong> Cabernet is the safer first purchase. Merlot can age, but Cabernet more consistently rewards patience.</p>

  <h2>Common Buying Mistakes</h2>

  <p>The biggest mistake is assuming Merlot is always simpler and Cabernet is always better. That is branding, not tasting. Great Merlot can be profound, and bad Cabernet can be expensive and disappointing.</p>

  <p>The second mistake is ignoring the meal. Cabernet with delicate food can feel too hard. Merlot with heavily charred steak can feel too soft. Match the wine's structure to the plate, not just the grape's reputation.</p>

  <p>The third mistake is buying by status without thinking about timing. Cabernet often needs more patience. Merlot is often the better move if you plan to open the bottle soon.</p>

  <h2>Expert Tips</h2>
  <ol class="list-decimal list-inside space-y-4 text-gray-700">
    <li>Serve Cabernet slightly warmer than Merlot if both wines are very young and tannic.</li>
    <li>Buy Merlot when the menu is mixed and you need one flexible red for the whole table.</li>
    <li>Buy Cabernet when the meal is beef-heavy or you want a bottle with more cellaring upside.</li>
    <li>Do not assume higher price means Cabernet is the better choice; the right structure matters more than status.</li>
    <li>If you dislike herbal notes, avoid cooler-climate Cabernet from weaker vintages.</li>
    <li>If you dislike plush softness, avoid overripe Merlot that tastes sweet and loose.</li>
    <li>Try both grapes from Bordeaux if you want the classic contrast fastest.</li>
    <li>Use food, not prestige, as the deciding factor when the two are close in quality.</li>
  </ol>

  <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
  <div class="space-y-6">
    <div>
      <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Which is better for beginners?</h3>
      <p class="text-gray-700">Merlot is usually the easier starting point because the tannins are softer and the fruit reads more immediately. Cabernet can feel harder and more angular if you are not used to structured red wine.</p>
    </div>
    <div>
      <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Which one ages better?</h3>
      <p class="text-gray-700">Cabernet Sauvignon usually has the stronger aging profile because it carries more tannin and backbone. Great Merlot can age well too, but Cabernet is the safer bet if cellaring is the goal.</p>
    </div>
    <div>
      <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Which offers better value?</h3>
      <p class="text-gray-700">Merlot often wins on value because it is less prestige-driven in the market. You can find excellent Merlot at prices where Cabernet starts charging for reputation as much as quality.</p>
    </div>
    <div>
      <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Can I swap one for the other with dinner?</h3>
      <p class="text-gray-700">Sometimes, but not always. Cabernet is stronger with fattier, charred, or more intense dishes. Merlot is better when the food is softer, earthier, or less heavy.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

